Recognising the model and made of car, based on image input¶

In this notebook, I will be developing a cutting-edge AI model that is capable of recognizing car images and outputting their corresponding make and model. To achieve this, I will be utilizing the renowned Stanford Car Dataset, which comprises over 16,000 high-quality car images, evenly split between training and testing data.

The primary goal of this model is to assist car enthusiasts and spotters who often capture unique and rare cars but struggle to identify their make and model. With the help of this advanced tool, they will be able to quickly and accurately identify any car by simply uploading an image, enhancing their overall car-spotting experience.

Process¶

To train this AI model, I will be utilizing a state-of-the-art deep learning technique called Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs). CNNs have demonstrated remarkable success in image classification tasks, making them a perfect choice for identifying the make and model of cars from their images.

In addition, I will explore the data using various techniques such as data visualization and statistical analysis to gain insights into the dataset's properties. I will also preprocess the data by resizing the images to a uniform size, converting them to RGB, and normalizing the pixel values to facilitate the training process.

Moreover, I will split the dataset into training, validation, and testing sets and train the model on the training set. I will then fine-tune the model using transfer learning techniques to further improve its accuracy. Finally, I will evaluate the model's performance on the testing set and make necessary adjustments to improve its accuracy.

Imports¶

  • NumPy - a library for working with arrays and numerical operations in Python.
  • Matplotlib - a plotting library used for creating visualizations such as line plots, scatter plots, histograms, and more.
  • Pandas - a library used for data manipulation and analysis.
  • Keras - a high-level neural networks API that can be used with different backends, including TensorFlow.
  • TensorFlow - an open-source software library used for dataflow and differentiable programming across a range of tasks.

Data visualistion of .mat file - TEST¶

To gain a better understanding of the labels in the dataset, we'll create visualizations of the .mat files that contain the label information. This will allow us to explore the structure and format of the labels and identify any patterns or trends that may be useful for our model.

In [ ]:
# Load the cars_annos.mat file into a Python dictionary
mat_contents = sio.loadmat('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.mat')

# Print out the names of the fields in the dictionary
print(mat_contents.keys())

dict_keys(['__header__', '__version__', '__globals__', 'annotations', 'class_names'])
In [ ]:
# Load the labels from the cars_annos.mat file
class_names = mat_contents['__globals__']

# Print the number of class names (image annotations)
num_annotations = len(class_names)
print("Number of image annotations:", num_annotations)

Number of image annotations: 0

It wouldn't work if use the annotations from the table to go through the images, because simply there aren't any available.

In [ ]:
# Display the keys in the loaded file
print("Keys in the mat file:", mat_contents.keys())

# Access and print the contents of specific keys
print("Contents of 'class_names':", mat_contents['class_names'])
print("Contents of 'annotations':", mat_contents['annotations'])

However we can verify that the data is correct, and it contains the cars models and makes. However, the paths are not correct, that's why we will fix it in the flattening process

Now, we are going to convert this .mat file, to something more uderstandable. By doing some research in Kaggle discussion around this data, I found this thread, which exlains how to open code the cars_annos.mat, which is the code below.

In [ ]:
def read_mat_to_df(file_path):
    np_array= loadmat(file_path, matlab_compatible=False, simplify_cells=True, chars_as_strings=True)
    df= pd.DataFrame(np_array['annotations'])
    if 'class_names' in np_array:
        class_names= list(np_array['class_names'])
        df['class_name']= df['class'].map(dict(enumerate(class_names, start=1)))
    # squeeze int-types
    for c, t in df.dtypes.iteritems():
        if t.kind == 'i':
            df[c]= df[c].astype('int16')
    if 'fname' in df.columns:
        df['relative_im_path']= 'resized_images/cars_train' + df['fname']
        df.drop(columns=['fname'], inplace=True)
    return df

cars_full= read_mat_to_df('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.mat')
cars_full.sample(50)

Resizing the images - DO NOT RUN¶

First we are going to check what a size of a random image, if by any chance it's already resized. Then we are going to resize all of them.

In [ ]:
dataset_path_train = '/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_train/cars_train'
# Get a list of all image files in the dataset
image_files = [os.path.join(dataset_path_train, f) for f in os.listdir(dataset_path_train) if f.endswith('.jpg')]

# Choose a random image file from the list
random_image_file = random.choice(image_files)

# Open the image file
image = Image.open(random_image_file)

# Get the dimensions of the image
width, height = image.size

# Display the image using matplotlib and add text to it
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.imshow(image)
ax.text(0.5, -0.2, f'Image is {width}x{height} pixels', transform=ax.transAxes, fontsize=12, ha='center')
plt.show()

A few run of the block of code above, shows that every image have a different size, so it's time to make them same size, due to two reasons:

  • A common image size for computer vision models is 224x224 pixels, which is the input size for many popular CNN architectures.This size is often used because it strikes a balance between detail and computing resources, and because many pre-trained models are available for this input size.

  • Another reason to resize the images to a common size is to ensure that they have the same dimensions for training the CNN model. CNNs require that all input images have the same width and height, as the number of weights in the model's layers is determined by the dimensions of the input.

## NOT WORKING

# Set the directory path to the dataset
dataset_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/'

# Creating the output directories for train and test data
output_dir_train = os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)/cars_train')
output_dir_test = os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)/cars_test')
os.makedirs(output_dir_train, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(output_dir_test, exist_ok=True)

# Load the labels
cars_annos = sio.loadmat(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'cars_annos.mat'))

# Transpose the annotations
annotations = np.transpose(cars_annos['annotations'])

# Create a dictionary mapping filenames to labels
filename_to_label = {}

# Process data for train and test separately
for annotation in annotations:
    try:
        filename = annotation[0][0][0][0].split('/')[-1]
        label = int(annotation[0][0][5][0][0]) - 1  # Convert label to int and subtract 1 to make the labels zero-indexed
        filename_to_label[filename] = label
    except (ValueError, IndexError):
        print(f"Skipping annotation with invalid format: {annotation}")

# Process data for both train and test
for dataset_type in ['train', 'test']:
    # Get the list of image files in the directory
    image_files = sorted(os.listdir(os.path.join(dataset_path, f'cars_{dataset_type}', f'cars_{dataset_type}')),
                         key=lambda x: int(x.split('.')[0]))

    # Initialize empty list for images and labels
    images = []
    labels = []

    # Loop through each image file in the directory
    for filename in image_files:
        # Adjust the path to match the location of the images
        filepath = os.path.join(dataset_path, f'cars_{dataset_type}', f'cars_{dataset_type}', filename)
        print("Processing image:", filepath)  # Print the filepath for debugging purposes

        # Check if the filename has a corresponding label in the dictionary
        if filename in filename_to_label:
            label = filename_to_label[filename]
        else:
            print(f"No label found for image: {filename}")
            continue

        # Load and process the image
        image = Image.open(filepath)
        resized_image = image.resize((224, 224))

        # Append the image and label to the lists
        images.append(np.array(resized_image.convert('RGB')))
        labels.append(label)

    # Convert the list of images and labels to numpy arrays
    X = np.array(images)
    y = np.array(labels)

    # Save the image data and labels into separate files
    output_filename = f'images_{dataset_type}.npz'
    output_label_filename = f'labels_{dataset_type}.npy'
    np.savez_compressed(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)', output_filename), X=X)
    np.save(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)', output_label_filename), y)

## NEW TRY WITH THE CSV

# Set the directory path to the dataset
dataset_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/'

# Creating the output directories for train and test data
output_dir_train = os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)/cars_train')
output_dir_test = os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)/cars_test')
os.makedirs(output_dir_train, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(output_dir_test, exist_ok=True)

# Load the labels from the CSV file
df_annotations = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'cars_annos.csv'))

# Create a dictionary mapping filenames to labels
filename_to_label = {row['relative_im_path']: row['class_name'] for _, row in df_annotations.iterrows()}

# Process data for both train and test
for dataset_type in ['train', 'test']:
    # Get the list of image files in the directory
    directory_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, f'cars_{dataset_type}')
    image_files = [f for f in os.listdir(directory_path) if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(directory_path, f))]

    image_files = sorted(image_files)

    # Initialize empty list for images and labels
    images = []
    labels = []

    # Loop through each image file in the directory
    for filename in image_files:
        # Adjust the path to match the location of the images
        filepath = os.path.join(directory_path, filename)
        print("Processing image:", filepath)  # Print the filepath for debugging purposes

        # Check if the filename has a corresponding label in the dictionary
        if filename in filename_to_label:
            label = filename_to_label[filename]
        else:
            print(f"No label found for image: {filename}")
            continue

        # Load and process the image
        image = Image.open(filepath)
        resized_image = image.resize((224, 224))

        # Append the image and label to the lists
        images.append(np.array(resized_image.convert('RGB')))
        labels.append(label)

    # Convert the list of images and labels to numpy arrays
    X = np.array(images)
    y = np.array(labels)

    # Save the image data and labels into separate files
    output_filename = f'images_{dataset_type}.npz'
    output_label_filename = f'labels_{dataset_type}.npy'
    np.savez_compressed(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)', output_filename), X=X)
    np.save(os.path.join(dataset_path, 'resized-data(v3)', output_label_filename), y)

# Load the .mat file
mat_contents = sio.loadmat('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.mat')

# Extract the annotations array
annotations = mat_contents['annotations']

# Extract the field names
field_names = annotations.dtype.names

# Create empty lists for each field
data = {field: [] for field in field_names}

# Iterate over the annotations and extract the field values
for annotation in annotations:
    for field in field_names:
        value = annotation[field][0][0]
        data[field].append(value)

# Create a DataFrame using the extracted data
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Save the DataFrame as a CSV file
df.to_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.csv', index=False)

In [ ]:
# Load the .mat file
mat = sio.loadmat('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.mat')

# Get the annotations and class_names structures
annotations = mat['annotations'][0]
class_names = mat['class_names'][0]

# Prepare a list to store annotations in a dictionary format
annotation_records = []

for annotation in annotations:
    record = {}
    record['relative_im_path'] = annotation[0][0]
    record['bbox_x1'] = int(annotation[1][0][0])
    record['bbox_y1'] = int(annotation[2][0][0])
    record['bbox_x2'] = int(annotation[3][0][0])
    record['bbox_y2'] = int(annotation[4][0][0])
    record['class'] = int(annotation[5][0][0])
    record['test'] = int(annotation[6][0][0])
    record['class_name'] = class_names[record['class'] - 1][0]  # Subtract 1 as class_names is 0-indexed

    # Add the dictionary to the list
    annotation_records.append(record)

# Convert the list of dictionaries to a pandas dataframe
df_annotations = pd.DataFrame(annotation_records)

# Write the dataframe to a .csv file
df_annotations.to_csv('cars_annos.csv', index=False)

# FIXING DATA

# Read the dataset from CSV file
df = pd.read_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/cars_annos.csv')

# Remove braces from columns
df['relative_im_path'] = df['relative_im_path'].str.strip("[]'")
df['bbox_x1'] = df['bbox_x1'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['bbox_y1'] = df['bbox_y1'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['bbox_x2'] = df['bbox_x2'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['bbox_y2'] = df['bbox_y2'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['class'] = df['class'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['test'] = df['test'].str.strip("[[]]").astype(int)
df['class_name'] = df['class_name'].str.strip("[]")

# Modify relative_im_path based on 'test' column
df['relative_im_path'] = df.apply(lambda row: f"cars_test/cars_test/{row['relative_im_path'].split('/')[-1]}" if row['test'] == 1 else f"cars_train/cars_train/{row['relative_im_path'].split('/')[-1]}", axis=1)

# Modify image naming convention
df['relative_im_path'] = df['relative_im_path'].apply(lambda x: x[:-10] + x[-9:])

In [ ]:
for label in filename_labels:
    try:
        int(label)
    except ValueError:
        print(f"Found a non-integer label: {label}")

The code above resizes each RGB image to 224x224 pixels and saves it to a new directory resized_images/cars_train. It then flattens each resized image by converting it to RGB format and calling the flatten method. This produces a 1D array of pixel values that can be used as input to the CNN model. Now lets do the same, for the cars_test images.

DO NOT RUN CODE BELOW¶

# Load the flattened images and labels from the files
train_data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_train/flattened_images_train.npy')
test_data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_test/flattened_images_test.npy')
train_labels = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_train/labels_train.npy')
test_labels = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_test/labels_test.npy')

# Print the shape of the arrays
print("Train data shape:", train_data.shape)
print("Train labels shape:", train_labels.shape)

print("Test data shape:", test_data.shape)
print("Test labels shape:", test_labels.shape)

Train data shape: (8079, 150528)
Train labels shape: (8079,)
Test data shape: (8000, 150528)
Test labels shape: (8000,)

How we can see, we 8079 train images, corresponding to 8079 labels, and 8000 test images, corresponding to 8000 labels. So it's all good.

Convolutional Base¶

In [ ]:
# Define the architecture
model = Sequential()

# Convolutional base
model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(224, 224, 3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Flatten())

# Fully connected layers
model.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))  # Dropout layer to reduce overfitting
model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))  # Another dropout layer
num_classes = 196;
model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))  # Final layer for classification

# Print the model summary
model.summary()

Compiling the model¶

In [ ]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
# Load the flattened train image data and labels
X_train = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_train/flattened_images_train.npy')
y_train = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/stanford-cars-dataset/resized-data(v2)/cars_train/labels_train.npy')

# Reshape the data
X_train = X_train.reshape(-1, 224, 224, 3)

# Train the model
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=32)
